**DO-WHILE** LOOP vs **FOR LOOP**

 - **DO-WHILE LOOP** will execute the code first, then check the condition.
 - **FOR LOOP** will check the condition first, then execute the code.

In your case: if side==0, i &lt; side will turn false in your &quot;FOR LOOP&quot; because (0 &lt; 0 is false).

So, what you have to do in your **DO-WHILE LOOP** is to check that **side must be bigger than 0** then run the loop because if side == 0, DO-WHILE LOOP will run once then finish because the condition is false. 

----------

```c++
    // OUTER FOR LOOP
    for (int i = 0; i &lt; side; i++) { 
    // int i = 0; means (create a variable i with initial value of 0)
    // i &lt; side; means (check if value of i is smaller than value of side)
    // i++; means (increase the value of i by 1 after everything in {} executed)
        // INNER FOR LOOP
    	cout &lt;&lt; &quot;\n&quot;;
    }
    
    // OUTER DO-WHILE LOOP
    int i = 0; // (create a variable i with initial value of 0)
    if (side &gt; 0) { // Why &quot;if&quot; statement is here? =&gt; check above explanation
    	do {
            // INNER DO-WHILE LOOP
    	    cout &lt;&lt; &quot;\n&quot;;
    		i++; // (increase the value of i by 1 after everything in {} executed)
    	} while (i &lt; side); // (check if value of i is smaller than value of side)
    }
```


----------

```c++
    // INNER FOR LOOP
	for (int j = i; j &gt;= 0; j--)
    // int j=i; means [create a new variable j which is equal to i]
    // j&gt;=0; means [check if j is bigger or equal to 0]
    // j--; means [decrease j after everything in {} executed]
	{
		cout &lt;&lt; &quot;#&quot;;
	}

    // INNER DO-WHILE LOOP
	int j = i; // [create a new variable j which is equal to i]
	do {
		cout &lt;&lt; &quot;#&quot;;
		j--; // [decrease j after everything in {} executed]
	} while (j &gt;= 0); // [check if j is bigger or equal to 0]
```

